Introduction

In this tutorial, we will demonstrate the basic steps involved in designing a linkage map. There are several well-established pipelines and resources available online that provide detailed instructions for building high-quality genetic maps. Some of the most commonly used software tools include R/qtl, OneMap, and MapPoly, all of which are R packages tailored for different types of populations and ploidy levels.

Here, our focus is on a simulated dataset, which allows us to explore the fundamental concepts behind map construction without the complexity of real-world data. This tutorial is intended as a conceptual introduction; for a deeper, more practical understanding of high-quality map construction, we encourage you to refer to dedicated tutorials and documentation provided by the developers of these tools.

Main computational tools and tutorials:

This table summarizes the key differences, best use cases, and resources for three popular R packages used in linkage mapping.

Package Best Forâ¦ Key Features When to Use Link
R/qtl Mapping QTL in inbred populations - QTL analysis (interval mapping, multiple imputation)
- Hidden Markov models
- Designed for common crosses (F2, backcross, RILs)		 Use when working with inbred-derived populations (e.g., F2, RILs, backcross). Great for teaching, simulation, and QTL analysis. R/qtl
OneMap Building maps for outcrossing species - Handles outcrosses
- Uses HMMs
- Marker ordering (RCD, TRY, SER, RECORD, UG)
- Dominant/co-dominant marker support		 Use for outcrossing populations or mixed marker types. Also supports some inbred crosses. OneMap (CRAN)
MAPpoly Polyploid species and large diploid datasets - Supports autopolyploids (up to 12-ploid)
- High marker capacity (>10,000)
- Graphical UI with VIEWpoly
- Imports from VCF and others		 Use for polyploid species (e.g., blueberry, potato) or when working with large-scale datasets that exceed the limits of other tools. MAPpoly (CRAN)

Summary

  • Use R/qtl for simple, inbred populations and QTL-focused workflows.
  • Use OneMap for non-inbred species and phase-unknown populations.
  • Use MAPpoly for polyploid genomes or high-density marker datasets.

Building Linkage Map for Inbred Diploid Populations with OneMap

In the figure below, we present the main steps to create a linkage map.

Main steps related to estimate a Linkage Map

Mapping Population

The first essential step in linkage map construction is to develop a suitable mapping population. This population must consist of individuals derived from a known crossâcommonly F2, backcross, recombinant inbred lines (RILs), or outcrossing full-sib populations. The choice of population type directly affects:

  • The expected segregation ratios,
  • The complexity of the analysis,

Once the population is established, all individuals (including the parents) must be genotyped using molecular markers such as SNPs, SSRs, or DArT markers. These markers are used to track the inheritance of alleles across the population.

After importing the data, the first analytical step is to test each marker for Mendelian segregation using a chi-square test. This helps identify markers that deviate from expected segregation ratios, which may indicate genotyping errors, selection, or other biological phenomena.

For the code below we will download a simulated example from the OneMap package. Some information:

  • OneMap can accept different inputs
  • In modern genotyping platforms, it is common to obtain high-density marker data, which often includes redundant markersâmarkers that are genetically identical or co-segregating. To address this redundancy, the functions find_bins() and create_data_bins()` in OneMap are used to identify and collapse these redundant markers into representative bins, similar to how LD pruning is applied in population genetics to reduce marker redundancy. This binning process simplifies the dataset without losing informative recombination signals, making map construction faster and more robust. Note: In this example, no redundant markers were simulated, so binning is not necessary.
library(onemap)
# Importing the data
setwd("/home/felipe/Dropbox (UFL)/classes/Molecular_Breeding/class1_linkageMapping")

Mendelian segregation distortion

In this example, we consider a backcross population consisting of 10 full-sib individuals genotyped at two codominant markers (Marker 1 and Marker 2). The genotypes were scored visually, simulating a gel image where bands represent alleles at different genomic loci. Since this is a backcross, we expect the Mendelian segregation ratio to be 1:1 (e.g., AA : Aa). By counting the observed genotypes for each marker, we can:

Visually inspect possible segregation distortion.

Example of gel image for 10 full-sib individuals genotyped at two codominant markers (Marker 1 and Marker 2)

# Marker 1: 8 AA, 2 Aa
obs_marker1 <- c(8, 2)
exp_marker1 <- c(5, 5)

chisq_test_marker1 <- chisq.test(x = obs_marker1, p = c(0.5, 0.5))
print(chisq_test_marker1)
## 
##  Chi-squared test for given probabilities
## 
## data:  obs_marker1
## X-squared = 3.6, df = 1, p-value = 0.05778
# Marker 2: 5 AA, 5 Aa
obs_marker2 <- c(5, 5)
exp_marker2 <- c(5, 5)

chisq_test_marker2 <- chisq.test(x = obs_marker2, p = c(0.5, 0.5))
print(chisq_test_marker2)
## 
##  Chi-squared test for given probabilities
## 
## data:  obs_marker2
## X-squared = 0, df = 1, p-value = 1

Interpretation

  • Marker 1: A Chi-square test will likely return a significant p-value, indicating segregation distortionâthe observed counts (8:2) deviate substantially from the expected 1:1 ratio.
  • Marker 2: The test will return a non-significant p-value, suggesting the observed 5:5 segregation is consistent with Mendelian expectations.
# Segregation test
bc_test <- test_segregation(bins_example)
no_dist <- select_segreg(bc_test, distorted = FALSE, numbers = TRUE) 
plot(bc_test)

Two-Point Analysis and Likelihood in a Backcross

The next step in linkage map construction is called two-point analysis. This involves estimating the recombination fraction (r) between all pairs of markers. The equations used to calculate these values depend on the type of mapping population, such as backcross (BC), F2, or recombinant inbred lines (RILs). In a backcross population, the calculation is relatively straightforward. The recombination fraction represents the proportion of recombinant individuals among the total and is bounded between 0 and 0.5 (no linkage). For each pair of markers, we estimate r by maximizing the likelihood function under the assumption of Mendelian segregation.

The likelihood function for a single marker pair in a backcross is given by:

\[ L(r) = (1 - r)^{n_{P}} \cdot r^{n_{R}} \]

Where:

  • \(r\) = recombination fraction (0 â¤ r â¤ 0.5)
  • \(n_P\) = number of parental-type individuals
  • \(n_R\) = number of recombinant-type individuals

This likelihood is maximized to estimate the most probable recombination fraction between the markers. To assess the statistical significance of linkage, we compute the LOD score (logarithm of the odds):

\[ \text{LOD} = \log_{10} \left( \frac{L(\hat{r})}{L(0.5)} \right) \]

Where:

  • \(\hat{r}\) = estimated recombination fraction
  • \(L(0.5)\) = likelihood under the null hypothesis of no linkage

A LOD score â¥ 3 is typically considered strong evidence for linkage.

The final goal of two-point analysis is to generate a matrix of pairwise recombination values and LOD scores, which will be used to construct linkage groups and marker order, as illustrated in the heatmap below.

Example of sequencial analyses in BC

library(onemap)
twopts_bc <-rf_2pts(bins_example, LOD = 3, max.rf = 0.5, verbose = TRUE, rm_mks = FALSE)
## Computing 2415 recombination fractions ...
print(twopts_bc, c("M1", "M2"))
##   Results of the 2-point analysis for markers: M1 and M2 
##   Criteria: LOD =  3 , Maximum recombination fraction =  0.5 
## 
##          rf         LOD 
##  0.03603604 25.93578305

Linkage Groups and Ordering

In linkage mapping, markers are grouped into linkage groups based on their genetic associations. This can be done using either heuristic methods or statistical methods, depending on the dataset and the software used.

Heuristic Method

  • If the recombination frequency (\(r\)) between two markers is less than 0.5 and the LOD score is greater than 3,
  • Then these two markers are considered to belong to the same linkage group.

Statistical Method

  • Uses clustering or grouping algorithms (e.g., UPGMA) to assign markers into linkage groups.
  • These methods are implemented in more recent linkage mapping software.
  • They can incorporate prior information, such as the expected number of chromosomes, to improve accuracy.
# Assigning markers to linkage groups
mark_no_dist <- make_seq(twopts_bc, c(no_dist))

# heuristic
LGs <- group(mark_no_dist, LOD=2, max.rf=0.2)

Final Map

Check list:

  • Marker Order Consistency: if we have reference genomes available, the order of markers should be biologically consistent. Also, if different algorithms (e.g.Â RECORD, Seriation, ripple) produce similar marker orders, that increases confidence in the map
  • Visual Inspection of Heatmaps: heatmaps of recombination fractions and LOD scores should show a clear diagonal pattern in each linkage group.
  • Inflate map distances: check for long gaps (> 10-20cM) and amount of missing data (or genotyping errors), it can inflate the map (> 150-200 cM is a red flag).
maps_list <- list(LG1_bc_final, LG2_bc_final,LG3_bc_final)
draw_map(maps_list, names = TRUE, grid = TRUE, cex.mrk = 0.7)

What we did not cover in this tutorial?

  • The use of priori information about reference genomes
  • More details about HMM and multipoint analyses
  • Other types of population mapping, including outcrossing species
  • Polyploid analyses

Conclusion

Despite advances in sequencing technologies and reference genome assemblies, linkage mapping remains a critical tool for uncovering the genetic architecture of traits, validating genome assemblies, infer haplotypes, and guiding marker-assisted selection in breeding programs.
